        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="x-oldsun-Latn">
                <p> 
                    <lb n="1"/><unclear>//</unclear> ba <num value="3">3</num> guna <num value="3">3</num> Apuy· <num value="3">3</num> 
                    <lb n="2"/>di vva<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied><!-- Dan: this is one of those cases of a writing tradition where missing anusvāras are so common that it is actually impossible to treat them as 'omitted'; what was the solution, even if only provisional, that we had decided upon recently? I don't see any trace of it in EG. --> <num value="1">1</num>, Iti sakakala rumata<lb 
                        n="3" break="no"/>k· disusu<supplied reason="omitted">k·</supplied><!-- Dan: here we confront a phenomenon that we may not yet have discussed for EG, namely a very strong scribal habit not to realize geminate consonants, but to spell only one. Here we have phonemic /susuk ku/, whiich is spelled in full would probably take the graphic form <susuk· ku> because in Sundanese script, ligatures are not used so freely. Now how to encode that we supply one of the expected two k's and how to decide on which word to supply it? I think we need to furnish guidance in EG.--> ku baṭāri hyaṁ pun·</p>
            </div>
        <div type="apparatus">
            <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                   <lem source="bib:HasanDjafar1991_01"><unclear>//</unclear> ba</lem>
                    <rdg source="bib:Holle1877_01">// baḥ</rdg>
                    <note>Instead of an opening punctuation sign, it may be possible to read <foreign>A</foreign>, in which case the first word would be <foreign>Aba</foreign>. Noorduyn (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Noorduyn1993_01"/><citedRange>313</citedRange></bibl>) notes that <foreign>ba</foreign> means 3 in one or more chronograms of the <title>Pararaton</title>. Zoetmulder (<bibl rend="omitname"><ptr target="bib:Zoetmulder1982_01"/><citedRange unit="entry">wā</citedRange><!-- Dan: we should probably add "entry" to the list of permit values for @unit in <citedRange> in EG. --></bibl>records the word <foreign>ba</foreign> as a synonym of <foreign>wā</foreign>: <quote>II 1. live coal, piece of burning material which is aglow</quote>, and <quote>2. = <foreign>ava</foreign> bright, clear, shining</quote>.</note>
                 </app>
                <app loc="3">
                    <lem>disusu<supplied reason="omitted">k·</supplied></lem>
                    <note>For the same phenomenon of consonant degemination, cf. manuscript Perpusnas L 426B, no. 13: <foreign>hya <choice><reg>pəpək ku</reg><orig>pəpəku</orig></choice> pənuḥ kita maṁke</foreign> "Now you are filled by fullness".<!-- Dan: what markup is needed for the quotation marks around a translation such as here? Use <quote>, as in other cases?--></note>
                </app>
            </listApp>  
            </div>            
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
                <p>Glowing 3 qualities 3 fires 3 in a human 1: that was the <supplied reason="subaudible">year in the</supplied> Śaka era that Rumatak was marked off by Bhaṭārī Hyaṅ. Finished.</p>
            </div>
